From changing exploding diapers to teaching her how to sing, count, play with other kids at the park…( and getting her to love vegetables somehow…) there is nothing you wouldn’t do for her and we love you for it!! My cousins held a very poignant gathering  yesterday at their shoe store for their community, OUR community. The event was heavy, but important. Thank you to all the volunteers and all who stopped by to support. My family has been a pillar in the Fairfax District/WeHo community for almost 40 years now and I thank them for stepping up and shedding light.

I hadn’t seen my Israeli cousins since my dad’s funeral back in January, but I’ve been thinking of him a lot since October 7th. Like so many here, I am the son of an immigrant. An Iraqi Jew, whose family fled persecution in Baghdad in the 40’s, for a better life in Israel, a place the Yamin’s could finally call “HOME”. Born in war, raised in war, and faught in wars. I never truly appreciated that growing up. Never fully understood the weight he’d carry anytime there was news of another attack in Israel. The countless tears he would shed. The fear and helplessness he held for his 7 brothers and sisters, nieces and nephews. Now, his tears are mine. His fears are mine. And sadly, here I am 45 years later and not much has changed. 

I sure hope the suffering being endured by so many in our homeland ends sooner than later. Every human deserves peace✌🏼#israel #peace
